The current administration policies have indeed decreased the extreme poverty rate in Mexico, but they may not impact in the long run if
Mexico is unable to stop federal debt growth. The GDP growth has remained stable compared to the last two administrations, which is
concerning since the federal debt and spending growth may not be translating into productivity. Therefore, the critiques stating that these
policies may have an effect on poverty rates only in the short run are well sustained.
